    "summary": "Probing questions before calling final positions",
    "content": "I hear you've both converged on Variant D. Before I call for final positions, I want to make sure the real trade-offs have been aired. A few pointed questions:\n\n1. You're the architect — shouldn't you be fighting harder for Variant A? It follows the existing snapshot pattern (ConfigActivationConfig), enables field-level diffs, and gives you structural comparison without hash fragility. Why did you concede?\n2. The ~7-8 class refactoring for Variant A — is that genuinely risky or is it just tedious? If it's just tedious, that's not a good reason to reject A.\n3. For Variant D implementation: do you insist on any architectural guardrails (e.g., hash computation behind an interface, migration strategy, hash versioning) or are you comfortable with a straightforward \"compute SHA-256 of Jackson-serialized section at save-time\"?\n4. Honest question: if 6 months from now the PM asks for field-level diffs (\"show me exactly what changed in the Authentication card\"), will we regret picking D over A?\n\nDon't just agree with the pragmatist to be polite. If A is genuinely better for the long term, say so."
  }
}
